            <div class="num">05 / 06 · Oversight-leaning</div>
            <h3>Civic Risk Steward</h3>
            <p class="def">Centers harm to specific publics — workers, minorities, civic infrastructure — over abstract capability or competition framings.</p>
            <ul class="diff-list">
              <li>Reads concentrated harms before aggregate gains</li>
              <li>Wants standing and remedy for affected groups</li>
            </ul>
            <div class="meta-row">
              <span><span class="k">Nearest</span><span class="nb">Democratic Guardrailist</span></span>
              <a class="open" href="#">Open in Field Guide ↗</a>
            </div>
          </div>
          <div class="right">
            <div class="fp">
              <div class="lbl"><span>Fingerprint</span><span class="scale">L · M · H</span></div>
              <div class="fp-row high"><span class="name">Oversight</span><div class="track"><span class="v" style="width:84%"></span></div></div>
              <div class="fp-row"><span class="name">Capability</span><div class="track"><span class="v" style="width:46%"></span></div></div>
              <div class="fp-row"><span class="name">Openness</span><div class="track"><span class="v" style="width:62%"></span></div></div>
              <div class="fp-row"><span class="name">Multilat.</span><div class="track"><span class="v" style="width:55%"></span></div></div>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <!-- 6 -->
        <div class="d2-card">
          <div class="left">
            <div class="num">06 / 06 · Cross-pressured</div>
            <h3>Multilateral Coordinator</h3>
            <p class="def">Looks for governance traction in regimes, standards bodies, and treaties; willing to trade national autonomy for credible coordination.</p>
            <ul class="diff-list">
              <li>Prefers shared compute and licensing baselines</li>
              <li>Names regime weakness rather than hiding it</li>
            </ul>
            <div class="meta-row">
              <span><span class="k">Nearest</span><span class="nb">Democratic Guardrailist</span></span>
              <a class="open" href="#">Open in Field Guide ↗</a>
            </div>
          </div>
          <div class="right">
            <div class="fp">
              <div class="lbl"><span>Fingerprint</span><span class="scale">L · M · H</span></div>
              <div class="fp-row"><span class="name">Oversight</span><div class="track"><span class="v" style="width:64%"></span></div></div>
              <div class="fp-row"><span class="name">Capability</span><div class="track"><span class="v" style="width:55%"></span></div></div>
              <div class="fp-row"><span class="name">Openness</span><div class="track"><span class="v" style="width:60%"></span></div></div>
              <div class="fp-row high"><span class="name">Multilat.</span><div class="track"><span class="v" style="width:88%"></span></div></div>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="fg-route">
        <p class="body">The Atlas is the browse map. <b>The AI Field Guide</b> carries the long-form: definitions in depth, the strongest critique of each pattern, and the per-archetype reading shelf — kept off the cards on purpose.</p>
        <a href="#">Open AI Field Guide <span class="arr">→</span></a>
      </div>
    </div>
  </article>

  <!-- ===========================================================
       Recommendation
       =========================================================== -->
  <section class="reco">
    <h2>Recommendation for fast scanning</h2>
    <p class="deck">Which direction to ship</p>

    <div class="reco-row">
      <div>
        <h3>01 · Index Shelf</h3>
        <p>Wins on calm. Six identical cells, no ornament, every archetype gets the same air. Best for a reader who arrives without a question and wants to read the patterns sequentially.</p>
        <p>Loses on at-a-glance comparison. The reader has to read text to tell two archetypes apart; nothing distinguishes them visually except their words.</p>
      </div>
      <div>
        <h3>02 · Fingerprint Row</h3>
        <p>Wins on scanning. The four-row fingerprint turns each archetype into a recognizable shape — Strategic Competitor reads as “tall capability, short openness” before the eye reaches the prose. Two passes get you a working map.</p>
        <p>Loses on density. The wider 2-up grid means the reader sees three archetypes per fold rather than six; comparison is faster but coverage is slower.</p>
      </div>
    </div>

    <p class="reco-verdict">For a <b>browse</b> page — where the user is sweeping to find the one or two archetypes that match a real question — <b>Direction 02 (Fingerprint Row)</b> is the better choice. The fingerprint encodes the differentiators visually, so the eye does the comparison and the text confirms; Direction 01 makes the eye work through prose. Direction 01 is the better fallback if the team decides differentiator <em>language</em>, not <em>shape</em>, is the editorial priority — but for fast scanning of six items, shape wins.</p>
  </section>
</div>
</body>
</html>
