<body>
<div class="showcase">
  <header class="show-head">
    <span>AI Field Guide · Landing · Desktop</span>
    <span>2 directions · for review</span>
  </header>
  <h1 class="show-title">AI Field Guide — two directions</h1>
  <p class="show-deck">Two takes on the AI Field Guide landing surface — the explainer that sits beside the AI Atlas. Both explain the 8 axes, where nearby archetypes part ways, how IR and AI cross-read, and where to start. Neither offers a second assessment; the futures appendix is clearly secondary and labeled optional / non-scored.</p>

  <!-- ===========================================================
       DIRECTION 01 — Reading Room
       =========================================================== -->
  <div class="dir-label">
    <span class="num">01</span>
    <span class="name">Reading Room</span>
    <span>Editorial spread · ruled grids · vertical sequence</span>
  </div>
  <div class="dir-rationale">
    <b>Why this avoids overload</b>
    Four short, ruled sections in a single column: 8 axes as a 4×2 index, four "where they part ways" pairs, an IR↔AI cross-read table, and a three-cell "start here" shelf. Each section is its own grid; the rules between cells do most of the structural work, so the reader's eye breaks the page into legible bricks instead of facing a wall. Futures sits at the bottom in a dashed-border block, visibly labeled non-scored. No score numbers anywhere.
  </div>

  <article class="frame" data-screen-label="01 AI Field Guide — Reading Room">
    <nav class="nav">
      <span class="brand">IR Worldview Inventory<span class="beta">Beta</span></span>
      <div class="nav-links">
        <a href="#">Foundation</a>
        <a href="#">Modules</a>
        <a href="#">AI Governance</a>
        <a href="#">Profile</a>
        <a href="#">Atlas</a>
        <a href="#" class="active">Field Guide</a>
      </div>
      <span style="font-family:'IBM Plex Mono', monospace; font-size:11px; color:var(--muted); letter-spacing:0.06em;">AI Field Guide</span>
    </nav>

    <div class="frame-inner">
      <p class="eyebrow">AI Field Guide<span class="sep">/</span>Explainer<span class="sep">/</span>Companion to the Atlas</p>
      <span class="non-score-banner"><b>Explainer</b> Reading surface only — no scoring, no second assessment.</span>
      <h1 class="title">A reader's companion to the AI Atlas — <em>not a second assessment</em>.</h1>
      <p class="deck-line">The Atlas shows the patterns; the Field Guide explains them. Eight axes that organize the patterns, four pairs where nearby archetypes part ways, a short IR ↔ AI cross-read, and a small reading shelf to start with.</p>

      <!-- 8 axes -->
      <h2 class="sec"><span class="num">§1</span>The eight axes</h2>
      <p class="sec-deck">What the axes describe — names, opposing poles, one sentence each. No scores; this is the vocabulary the Atlas uses.</p>
      <div class="d1-axes">
        <div class="d1-axis"><div class="num">A1</div><div class="nm">Public oversight</div><div class="poles">DELEGATION ── OVERSIGHT</div><div class="desc">How much accountability is required before deployment.</div></div>
        <div class="d1-axis"><div class="num">A2</div><div class="nm">Capability pace</div><div class="poles">SLOW ── PUSH</div><div class="desc">How aggressively to advance frontier capability against risk.</div></div>
        <div class="d1-axis"><div class="num">A3</div><div class="nm">Openness</div><div class="poles">CLOSED ── OPEN</div><div class="desc">Default toward release of weights, data, and methods.</div></div>
        <div class="d1-axis"><div class="num">A4</div><div class="nm">Concentration</div><div class="poles">DIFFUSE ── CONCENTRATED</div><div class="desc">Tolerance for a few labs holding most frontier capability.</div></div>
        <div class="d1-axis"><div class="num">A5</div><div class="nm">Legitimacy &amp; rule-setting</div><div class="poles">PROCEDURAL ── SUBSTANTIVE</div><div class="desc">Where governance authority is grounded.</div></div>
        <div class="d1-axis"><div class="num">A6</div><div class="nm">Competition vs coordination</div><div class="poles">COORDINATE ── COMPETE</div><div class="desc">How much to read AI as state competition vs shared problem.</div></div>
        <div class="d1-axis"><div class="num">A7</div><div class="nm">Harm centering</div><div class="poles">AGGREGATE ── CONCENTRATED</div><div class="desc">Whose harms count first when tradeoffs appear.</div></div>
        <div class="d1-axis"><div class="num">A8</div><div class="nm">Instruments</div><div class="poles">RIGHTS ── INDUSTRIAL</div><div class="desc">Whether rules act through individual rights or industrial policy.</div></div>
      </div>

      <!-- Where they part ways -->
      <h2 class="sec"><span class="num">§2</span>Where nearby archetypes part ways</h2>
      <p class="sec-deck">Pairs that share most of their fingerprint. The split is what tells them apart.</p>
      <div class="d1-parts">
        <div class="d1-part">
          <div class="pair">Pair · A</div>
          <h4>Democratic Guardrailist <em>vs</em> Civic Risk Steward</h4>
          <div class="splits"><b>The split</b>Both center oversight. Guardrailist binds it to procedural legitimacy and public institutions; Steward binds it to specific publics and concentrated harms.</div>
        </div>
        <div class="d1-part">
          <div class="pair">Pair · B</div>
          <h4>Strategic Competitor <em>vs</em> Industrial Statist</h4>
          <div class="splits"><b>The split</b>Both treat AI as state-level. Competitor reads it through capability edge; Statist reads it through instruments — procurement, subsidy, standards.</div>
        </div>
        <div class="d1-part">
          <div class="pair">Pair · C</div>
          <h4>Open Ecosystem Builder <em>vs</em> Civic Risk Steward</h4>
          <div class="splits"><b>The split</b>Both worry about concentration. Builder defaults to release as the cure; Steward defaults to standing and remedy for affected groups.</div>
        </div>
        <div class="d1-part">
          <div class="pair">Pair · D</div>
          <h4>Multilateral Coordinator <em>vs</em> Democratic Guardrailist</h4>
          <div class="splits"><b>The split</b>Both want rules. Coordinator looks outward to regimes and standards bodies; Guardrailist looks inward to domestic accountability.</div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <!-- IR x AI cross-read -->
      <h2 class="sec"><span class="num">§3</span>How IR and AI cross-read</h2>
      <p class="sec-deck">The Compass is a related layer, not a parallel scoring system. Three places the two views converge — and the move each one makes.</p>
      <div class="d1-cross">
        <div class="d1-cross-row head">
          <div>Where they meet</div>
          <div>What IR adds</div>
          <div>What AI adds</div>
        </div>
        <div class="d1-cross-row">
          <div class="key">Public oversight ↔ Legitimacy</div>
          <div>IR debates whether legitimacy is procedural or substantive across regimes.</div>
          <div>AI asks who has standing to audit a model and on what authority.</div>
        </div>
        <div class="d1-cross-row">
          <div class="key">Competition ↔ Capability</div>
          <div>IR names the security dilemma; competition can be self-fulfilling.</div>
          <div>AI tests how much pace pressure is real vs how much is invoked.</div>
        </div>
        <div class="d1-cross-row">
          <div class="key">Markets ↔ Concentration</div>
          <div>IR's political economy lens reads dependence and coercion.</div>
          <div>AI surfaces compute and data concentration as a governance question.</div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <!-- Where to start reading -->
      <h2 class="sec"><span class="num">§4</span>Where to start reading</h2>
      <p class="sec-deck">Three small entry points, depending on what you came here to do.</p>
      <div class="d1-start">
        <div class="d1-start-cell">
          <div class="lbl">If you took the Compass</div>
          <h4>Read your archetype's nearest neighbor first</h4>
          <p>The archetype next to yours is where the editorial argument is sharpest. The Atlas card lists it; the Field Guide explains why.</p>
          <a href="#">Open neighbor pages →</a>
        </div>
        <div class="d1-start-cell">
          <div class="lbl">If you came from IR</div>
          <h4>Start with the cross-read above</h4>
          <p>Three places where IR concepts and AI governance vocabulary meet. The translation is uneven, on purpose.</p>
          <a href="#">Open IR ↔ AI cross-read →</a>
        </div>
        <div class="d1-start-cell">
          <div class="lbl">If you came to browse</div>
          <h4>Open the Atlas</h4>
          <p>The Atlas is the compact map of patterns. Field Guide is the explainer behind each card.</p>
          <a href="#">Open AI Atlas →</a>
        </div>
      </div>

      <!-- Futures appendix -->
      <div class="d1-futures">
        <div class="lbl">Appendix · Futures <span class="pill">Optional · Non-scored</span></div>
        Three short scenarios — Concentration tightens, Open weights win, Multilateral baseline holds — used in Field Guide entries to test the patterns. They are reading prompts, not predictions, and they do not enter any score on any page.
      </div>
    </div>
  </article>

  <!-- ===========================================================
       DIRECTION 02 — Two-Column Explainer
       =========================================================== -->
  <div class="dir-label">
    <span class="num">02</span>
    <span class="name">Two-Column Explainer</span>
    <span>Sticky left rail · numbered sections on the right</span>
  </div>
  <div class="dir-rationale">
    <b>Why this avoids overload</b>
    A persistent left rail labels what's on the page (axes, splits, cross-read, start, futures) and lets the reader skip without scrolling. The right column never holds more than one section at a time on the eye; each section uses ruled rows, not paragraphs. Futures is the last item in the rail, marked "optional" with a pill, and visually demoted via dashed border. Everything is reading vocabulary, not assessment.
  </div>

  <article class="frame" data-screen-label="02 AI Field Guide — Two-Column Explainer">
    <nav class="nav">
      <span class="brand">IR Worldview Inventory<span class="beta">Beta</span></span>
      <div class="nav-links">
        <a href="#">Foundation</a>
        <a href="#">Modules</a>
        <a href="#">AI Governance</a>
        <a href="#">Profile</a>
        <a href="#">Atlas</a>
        <a href="#" class="active">Field Guide</a>
      </div>
      <span style="font-family:'IBM Plex Mono', monospace; font-size:11px; color:var(--muted); letter-spacing:0.06em;">AI Field Guide</span>
    </nav>

    <div class="frame-inner">
      <p class="eyebrow">AI Field Guide<span class="sep">/</span>Explainer<span class="sep">/</span>Companion to the Atlas</p>
      <span class="non-score-banner"><b>Explainer</b> Reading surface only — no scoring, no second assessment.</span>
      <h1 class="title">A reader's companion to the AI Atlas — <em>browse, don't measure</em>.</h1>
      <p class="deck-line">Four short sections, plus an optional futures appendix. Use the left rail to skip; nothing here scores you, and there is no quiz on this page.</p>

      <div class="d2-layout">
        <aside class="d2-rail">
          <div class="lbl">On this page</div>
          <ol>
            <li class="active">The eight axes</li>
