  </article>

  <!-- recommendation -->
  <section class="reco">
    <h2>How each one avoids overloading the reader</h2>
    <p class="deck">Same content, different rhythms</p>
    <div class="reco-row">
      <div>
        <h3>01 · Reading Room</h3>
        <p>Vertical sequence. Each section is a ruled grid that the eye can scan as a single unit; the rules between cells do the structural work, so the reader never faces a paragraph longer than three sentences.</p>
        <p>Best for the user who reads top-to-bottom and wants the page to feel like a printed spread.</p>
      </div>
      <div>
        <h3>02 · Two-Column Explainer</h3>
        <p>Persistent left rail. The reader can see the whole page's contents without scrolling and skip directly to the section they want. Futures is visibly the last item, pilled "optional," and demoted to dashed border.</p>
        <p>Best for the user who arrives with a question — "where do Compass and IR meet?" — and wants to land in §3 immediately.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>
</div>
