              <span><span class="ln"></span>Baseline · Foundation</span>
              <span><span class="ln pres"></span>Under module pressure</span>
            </div>
            <p class="d2-callout">
              The widest gap is on <b>Competition</b> — module cases pulled you toward a more competition-centered read than your Foundation answers alone suggested. <b>Oversight</b> barely moved.
            </p>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="fold"><span>Fold · 900 px</span></div>
    <div class="below-fold">
      <div class="ghost mid"></div>
      <div class="ghost short"></div>
      <div class="ghost mid"></div>
    </div>
  </article>

  <!-- =========================================================
       DIRECTION 03 — ANCHORED SPREAD
       ========================================================= -->
  <div class="dir-label">
    <span class="num">03</span>
    <span class="name">Anchored Spread</span>
    <span>Baseline is the vertical anchor · lanes deviate left or right under pressure</span>
  </div>
  <div class="dir-rationale">
    <b>Why this reduces synthesis burden</b>
    The chart treats the baseline as the reference and shows only the <em>deviation</em> under pressure. Long bar = changed most; no bar = stayed stable; left vs right tells you which way you bent. This makes the four questions answerable in one downward scan: the headline labels the baseline, the longest bar names what changed most, the empty rows name what held, and the CTA row routes to the relevant result page for whichever lane the reader wants to open. AI is one strip below the chart — present, not pretending to be parallel.
  </div>

  <article class="frame" data-screen-label="03 Profile — Anchored Spread">
    <nav class="nav">
      <div>
        <span class="brand">IR Worldview Inventory<span class="beta">Beta</span></span>
