<article class="page">

  <header class="masthead">
    <span>Editorial Red Team · Confidential Draft</span>
    <span class="right">v1 · For author review</span>
  </header>

  <h1 class="doc-title">A worldview about worldviews — and what to question in it</h1>
  <p class="doc-sub">A red team of the IR Worldview Inventory beta. Read the headline label as a finished verdict and you miss the careful machinery underneath; read the machinery uncritically and you risk treating an editorial heuristic as a measurement instrument. This memo is the friction in between.</p>

  <dl class="meta-grid">
    <dt>Subject</dt><dd>IR Worldview Inventory · Beta · By JinHua Yip</dd>
    <dt>Surfaces reviewed</dt><dd>Landing, Foundation questionnaire, Foundation result, Security &amp; Strategy module, Technology &amp; Geoeconomics module, AI Governance Compass, Profile, Atlas, Field guide</dd>
    <dt>Posture</dt><dd>Adversarial but constructive. The aim is to harden the product, not to talk it out of existing.</dd>
    <dt>Severity key</dt><dd>High = trust risk · Medium = polish or precision risk · Low = nice-to-have · Structural = scope-level</dd>
  </dl>

  <section class="lead">
    <p>This is a serious editorial product. It is unusually careful about what it does <em>not</em> claim — the Methods note, the &ldquo;not yet modeled&rdquo; section on feminist, postcolonial, green and English School IR, the explicit framing that Atlas is &ldquo;a browse map, not a live user distribution&rdquo; — and that care is doing real work. Most online quizzes drape themselves in the costume of measurement and do not earn it. This one keeps stripping the costume off.</p>
    <p>Which is exactly why it is worth red-teaming hard. The product&rsquo;s strongest move — telling the user this is an interpretive instrument, not a diagnostic — is also its most fragile, because almost every other surface still <em>behaves</em> like a diagnostic: scored axes to one decimal, named archetypes in serif caps, a Profile that aggregates &ldquo;saved layers,&rdquo; a result-page reading shelf curated to the label. The disclaimer fights an uphill battle against the visual grammar.</p>
    <p>The findings below are organized from most consequential to least: what could erode user trust if a thoughtful reader pushed on it, what would sharpen the editorial voice, and what to flag for next-version scope. Where useful, I&rsquo;ve drafted concrete revision language rather than gestured at it.</p>
  </section>

  <div class="key" aria-label="Severity key">
